itional ecological models become impractical with the inclusion of behavior, and the optimization approaches of behavioral ecology cannot be used when future conditions are unpredictable due to feedbacks from the behavior of other individuals. This book provides a comprehensive introduction to state- and prediction-based theory, or SPT, a powerful new approach to modeling trade-off behaviors in contexts such as individual-based population models where feedbacks and variability make optimization impossible.Modeling Populations of Adaptive Individuals features a wealth of examples that range from highly simplified behavior models to complex population models in which individuals make adaptive trade-off decisions about habitat and activity selection in highly heterogeneous environments. Steven Railsback and Bret Harvey explain how SPT builds on key concepts from the state-based dynamic modeling theory of behavioral ecology, and how it combines explicit predictions of future conditions with approximations of a fitness measure to represent how individuals make good-not optimal-decisions that they revise as conditions change. The resulting models are realistic, testable, adaptable, and invaluable for answering fundamental questions in ecology and forecasting ecological outcomes of real-world scenarios.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAdaptation (Biology) 0aAdaptation (Biology). 0aEcology. 0aPopulation biologyxMathematical models. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Ecology.2bisacsh  aAlasdair I. Houston.  aColin W. Clark.  aDynamic Modeling in Behavioral Ecology.  aDynamic State Variable Models in Ecology.  aJohn M. NcNamara.  aMarc Mangel.  aModels of Adaptive Behaviour.  aactivity selection.  aadaptive behavior.  abehavioral ecology.  acompetition.  adecision algorithm.  adynamic state variable m